                <div id="toc"></div>
	<script>
		$('#toc').toc({
		    'selectors': 'h1,h2,h3', //elements to use as headings
		    'container': 'body', //element to find all selectors in
		    'smoothScrolling': true, //enable or disable smooth scrolling on click
		    'prefix': 'toc', //prefix for anchor tags and class names
		    'onHighlight': function(el) {}, //called when a new section is highlighted 
		    'highlightOnScroll': true, //add class to heading that is currently in focus
		    'highlightOffset': 100, //offset to trigger the next headline
		    'anchorName': function(i, heading, prefix) { //custom function for anchor name
			return prefix+i;
		    },
		    'headerText': function(i, heading, $heading) { //custom function building the header-item text
			return $heading.text();
		    },
		'itemClass': function(i, heading, $heading, prefix) { // custom function for item class
		  return $heading[0].tagName.toLowerCase();
		}
		});
	</script>

	<p id="scenario">Imagine the world at war. Let's be realistic, and go with <b><span style="color: #C0392B">USA</span> & <span style="color: #2980B9" >Russia</span></b> - a showdown played out in Olympic hockey rinks for decades. Let's think about that for a moment. Not diplomatic threats, not puppet wars, but actual, full-out wars with the two countries with the most nukes and allies (in that order) than any other country or trans-national organization <b>on the planet</b>.	</p>
<p>Russia exports plywood and oil. They also export Russian crabs and vodka, but they aren't significant at this moment. What does matter, however, is plywood and oil. We rely <b>heavily</b> on Russia for oil, so we'd essentially have to chose between heating New York City or powering the gas-guzzling aircraft carriers that are the workhorses of our Navy.</p>

